TULAREMIA - RUSSIA (EUROPEAN)
*****************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Sponsored in part by Elsevier, publisher of
Drug Resistance Updates
<http://intl.elsevierhealth.com/journals/drup>
[1]
Date: Mon, 29 Aug 2005
From: Natalia Pshenichnaya <crane@aaanet.ru>
Source: News Agency Regions.ru [trans. Corresp.NP; edited]
<http://www.regions.ru/article/any/id/1874781.html>

According to the Territorial Management of the Federal Service, on 26 Aug
2005, 334 people with symptoms of tularemia, including 54 cases among children
under 14 years of age, have been reported in the Nizhny Novgorod, Voronezh,
Moscow, and Vladimir regions. The diagnosis has been laboratory-confirmed in
128 persons; confirmation in the others is pending.
135 people with such symptoms, including 26 children, have been registered in
the Moscow region, mostly among inhabitants of the Shatursky district. All the
affected people have been hospitalized. In 33 persons, the diagnosis has been
laboratory-confirmed. 23 have been discharged from the hospital.
99 people with symptoms of tularemia have been registered in the Nizhny
Novgorod region, 17 of whom are children. 66 are inhabitants of Dzerzhinsk,
and 33 are from Nizhny Novgorod. The diagnosis has been laboratory-confirmed
in 43 people, including 18 children.
82 cases have been reported in Gorohovetskiy district of the Vladimir region
where victims have summer residences; 12 of these people were believed to have
been infected in the Nizhny Novgorod region; 3 in the Ryazan and 2 in the
Ivanovo region.
67 people with symptoms of tularemia have been registered in the July-August
2005 period in the Ryazan area, including 5 children. 50 have been
hospitalized. In 25 people from the Klepikovsky district, the diagnosis has
been laboratory-confirmed.

28 people with symptoms of tularemia have been detected in the Voronezh
region, including 6 children: Voronezh - 25 cases, Liskinsky district - 2
cases, and Buturlinsky district - 1 case. In 22 patients the diagnosis has
been confirmed in the laboratory. Infection in urban dwellers has taken place
during visits to rural settlements.
All affected people have recalled bites by horseflies or other blood-sucking
insects, or bathing in open reservoirs in areas where the infection is
naturally endemic in wildlife.
--
